{"title_page": "ZIL-4104", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile\n| image        = Limusina ZiL-115 - San Petersburgo-007.jpg\n| name         = ZIL-4104\n| manufacturer = [[ZiL|Zavod Imeni Likhacheva]]\n| production   = {{ubl|1978&ndash;1983|106 built}}\n| class        = [[Luxury car]]\n| layout       = [[FR layout]] \n| predecessor  = [[ZIL-114]]\n| successor    = [[ZIL-41047|ZIL-41041/ZIL-41047]]\n| engine       = 7.7L ''ZIL-4104'' V8\n| transmission = {{ubl|2-speed automatic (1978\u20131983)|3-speed automatic (1984\u20131985)}}\n}}\n[[File:Zil-115.JPG|thumb|right|Zil 115]]\n\nThe '''ZIL-4104''' was a [[limousine]] built by [[ZiL]] from the late 1970s to the early 1980s, when it served as the transport of the elite of the [[Soviet Union]]. It is estimated that no more than fifty cars were produced each year.\n\nOriginally designated '''ZiL-115''',<ref>Thompson, Andy. ''Cars of the Soviet Union'' (Haynes Publishing, Somerset, UK, 2008), p.218.</ref> the ZIL-4104 was an update of the [[ZIL-114]] with which it shared the same [[chassis]] and over half its mechanical components.<ref>Thompson, p.218.</ref> Despite sharing the same chassis, the ZIL-4104 was as much as 314 [[kilogram|kg]] (692 [[pound (mass)|lb]]) heavier than the 114.\n\n<gallery>\nLimusina ZiL-115 - San Petersburgo-007.jpg|\nLimusina ZiL-115 - San Petersburgo-001.jpg|ZIL 115 (year 2018) \nLimusina ZiL-115 - San Petersburgo-008.jpg|\n</gallery>\n\nMechanically, the ZIL-4104 also improved on the 114. The [[pushrod]] [[V8 engine|V8]] engine of the 114 had its stroke increased from {{Convert|95|mm|in|abbr=on}} to {{Convert|105|mm|in|abbr=on}}. With a {{Convert|108|mm|in|abbr=on}} bore, this meant the capacity increased from {{convert|6,959|cc|cid|1|abbr=on}} to {{convert|7,695|cc|cid|abbr=on}},<ref>Thompson, pp.217 & 219.</ref> which was throughout the model's lifespan one of the world's biggest passenger-car engines (Cadillac offered a {{convert|472|cid|cc|abbr=on}} engine, enlarged to {{convert|500|cid|cc|abbr=on}}). This engine developed 315&nbsp;hp SAE Gross at 4,400 revs per minute and a substantial {{convert|608|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} at 2500 rpm.<ref>Thompson, p.219.</ref> The car weighs {{convert|3400|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, is {{Convert|6339|mm|in|abbr=on}} long, {{Convert|2068|mm|in|abbr=on}} wide, and {{Convert|1500|mm|in|abbr=on}} high.\n\nAmong its special features were special laminated windscreen and triple-layered windows, supposedly offering protection from [[radiation]] in case of [[nuclear warfare|nuclear attack]], plus duplicated systems, including dual [[ignition system|ignition]], two 74-[[ampere|amp]] [[Battery (electrical)|batteries]] in parallel, and two fuel pumps.<ref>Thompson, pp.219-220.</ref>\n\nThe console and dash were covered with [[Karelia]]n [[Betula pendula|birch]] {{Convert|10|mm|in|abbr=on}} thick, and the rear seat controlled radio (a ''Riga'' receiver), power windows, heater, and air conditioner; in the console in front was a ''Vilma'' [[cassette player]].<ref>Thompson, p.220.</ref>\n\nThe fuel tank was {{convert|120|L|usgal impgal|abbr=on}} and the car used leaded 95 [[octane]] petrol, getting {{convert|22|L/100 km|mpgus mpgimp|abbr=on}}.<ref>Thompson, p.219.</ref>\n\nBy 1984, a new three-speed [[automatic transmission]] had replaced the much outdated two-speed type that had been used by ZIL dating back to the first [[ZIL-111]] in 1958.\n\nAs [[official state car]]s, the ZiL-4104s were \"built under conditions of strict secrecy\" and were \"maintained in closed garages by a special division of the [[KGB]]\", with everyone involved in building and servicing them sworn to secrecy.<ref>Thompson, p.220.</ref>\n\n==Variants==\n*ZIL-4104: Base model. Also known as ZIL-115; produced 1978-1983.\n*ZIL-4105: Armored version of 4104.\n*ZIL-41042: Ambulance version. Also known as ZIL-115A.\n*ZIL-41043: As 41042 except with communications equipment.\n*ZIL-41044: Short wheelbase convertible version.\n*ZIL-41045: Restyled ZIL-4104. Produced 1983-1985.\n*ZIL-41046: Radio car version. \n*ZIL-41048: ZIL-4104 with automatic climate control. Produced in 1984.\n*ZIL-41051<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/Bj5DpwjFb_I/</ref>: Armored version of 41045.\n\n==ZIL-41044 and ZIL-41042==\nIn the later years of the 4104 production run, ZIL introduced two derived models based on the 4104 chassis and the shortened [[ZIL-117]] chassis not previously used with the 7.7 litre engine.\n\n*The 41044 was a shorter-wheelbase [[convertible]]. Unlike previous ZIL convertibles, it had only two doors but otherwise it was typically ZIL.\n*The 41042 was a rare station wagon produced by ZIL, but the few examples built were used as [[ambulances]] for general secretaries in the Soviet Union.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* Thompson, Andy. ''Cars of the Soviet Union''. Somerset, UK: Haynes Publishing,  2008.\n{{commons category|ZiL-4104}}\n\n{{ZIL timeline 1960-present}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zil-4104}}\n[[Category:Cars of Russia]]\n[[Category:ZiL vehicles|4104]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1978]]\n[[Category:1980s cars]]\n[[Category:Luxury vehicles]]\n[[Category:Soviet automobiles]]\n[[Category:Flagship vehicles]]\n[[Category:Limousines]]\n[[Category:Hearses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n| image        = Limusina ZiL-115 - San Petersburgo-007.jpg\n| name         = ZIL-4104\n| manufacturer = [[ZiL|Zavod Imeni Likhacheva]]\n| production   = {{ubl|1978&ndash;1983|106 built}}\n| class        = [[Luxury car]]\n| layout       = [[FR layout]] \n| predecessor  = [[ZIL-114]]\n| successor    = [[ZIL-41047|ZIL-41041/ZIL-41047]]\n| engine       = 7.7L ''ZIL-4104'' V8\n| transmission = {{ubl|2-speed automatic (1978\u20131983)|3-speed automatic (1984\u20131985)}}\n}}\n[[File:Zil-115.JPG|thumb|right|Zil 115]]\n\nThe '''ZIL-4104''' was a [[limousine]] built by [[ZiL]] from the late 1970s to the early 1980s, when it served as the transport of the elite of the [[Soviet Union]]. It is estimated that no more than fifty cars were produced each year.\n\nOriginally designated '''ZiL-115''',<ref>Thompson, Andy. ''Cars of the Soviet Union'' (Haynes Publishing, Somerset, UK, 2008), p.218.</ref> the ZIL-4104 was an update of the [[ZIL-114]] with which it shared the same [[chassis]] and over half its mechanical components.<ref>Thompson, p.218.</ref> Despite sharing the same chassis, the ZIL-4104 was as much as 314 [[kilogram|kg]] (692 [[pound (mass)|lb]]) heavier than the 114.\n\n<gallery>\nLimusina ZiL-115 - San Petersburgo-007.jpg|\nLimusina ZiL-115 - San Petersburgo-001.jpg|ZIL 115 (year 2018) \nLimusina ZiL-115 - San Petersburgo-008.jpg|\n</gallery>\n\nMechanically, the ZIL-4104 also improved on the 114. The [[pushrod]] [[V8 engine|V8]] engine of the 114 had its stroke increased from {{Convert|95|mm|in|abbr=on}} to {{Convert|105|mm|in|abbr=on}}. With a {{Convert|108|mm|in|abbr=on}} bore, this meant the capacity increased from {{convert|6,959|cc|cid|1|abbr=on}} to {{convert|7,695|cc|cid|abbr=on}},<ref>Thompson, pp.217 & 219.</ref> which was throughout the model's lifespan one of the world's biggest passenger-car engines (Cadillac offered a {{convert|472|cid|cc|abbr=on}} engine, enlarged to {{convert|500|cid|cc|abbr=on}}). This engine developed 315&nbsp;hp SAE Gross at 4,400 revs per minute and a substantial {{convert|608|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} at 2500 rpm.<ref>Thompson, p.219.</ref> The car weighs {{convert|3400|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, is {{Convert|6339|mm|in|abbr=on}} long, {{Convert|2068|mm|in|abbr=on}} wide, and {{Convert|1500|mm|in|abbr=on}} high.\n\nAmong its special features were special laminated windscreen and triple-layered windows, supposedly offering protection from [[radiation]] in case of [[nuclear warfare|nuclear attack]], plus duplicated systems, including dual [[ignition system|ignition]], two 74-[[ampere|amp]] [[Battery (electrical)|batteries]] in parallel, and two fuel pumps.<ref>Thompson, pp.219-220.</ref>\n\nThe console and dash were covered with [[Karelia]]n [[Betula pendula|birch]] {{Convert|10|mm|in|abbr=on}} thick, and the rear seat controlled radio (a ''Riga'' receiver), power windows, heater, and air conditioner; in the console in front was a ''Vilma'' [[cassette player]].<ref>Thompson, p.220.</ref>\n\nThe fuel tank was {{convert|120|L|usgal impgal|abbr=on}} and the car used leaded 95 [[octane]] petrol, getting {{convert|22|L/100 km|mpgus mpgimp|abbr=on}}.<ref>Thompson, p.219.</ref>\n\nBy 1984, a new three-speed [[automatic transmission]] had replaced the much outdated two-speed type that had been used by ZIL dating back to the first [[ZIL-111]] in 1958.\n\nAs [[official state car]]s, the ZiL-4104s were \"built under conditions of strict secrecy\" and were \"maintained in closed garages by a special division of the [[KGB]]\", with everyone involved in building and servicing them sworn to secrecy.<ref>Thompson, p.220.</ref>\n\n==Variants==\n*ZIL-4104: Base model. Also known as ZIL-115; produced 1978-1983.\n*ZIL-4105: Armored version of 4104.\n*ZIL-41042: Ambulance version. Also known as ZIL-115A.\n*ZIL-41043: As 41042 except with communications equipment.\n*ZIL-41044: Short wheelbase convertible version.\n*ZIL-41045: Restyled ZIL-4104. Produced 1983-1985.\n*ZIL-41046: Radio car version. \n*ZIL-41048: ZIL-4104 with automatic climate control. Produced in 1984.\n*ZIL-41051<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/Bj5DpwjFb_I/</ref>: Armored version of 41045.\n\n==ZIL-41044 and ZIL-41042==\nIn the later years of the 4104 production run, ZIL introduced two derived models based on the 4104 chassis and the shortened [[ZIL-117]] chassis not previously used with the 7.7 litre engine.\n\n*The 41044 was a shorter-wheelbase [[convertible]]. Unlike previous ZIL convertibles, it had only two doors but otherwise it was typically ZIL.\n*The 41042 was a rare station wagon produced by ZIL, but the few examples built were used as [[ambulances]] for general secretaries in the Soviet Union.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* Thompson, Andy. ''Cars of the Soviet Union''. Somerset, UK: Haynes Publishing,  2008.\n{{commons category|ZiL-4104}}\n\n{{ZIL timeline 1960-present}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zil-4104}}\n[[Category:Cars of Russia]]\n[[Category:ZiL vehicles|4104]]\n[[Category:1970s cars]]\n[[Category:1980s cars]]\n[[Category:Luxury vehicles]]\n[[Category:Soviet automobiles]]\n[[Category:Flagship vehicles]]\n[[Category:Limousines]]\n[[Category:Hearses]]\n", "name_user": "TKOIII", "label": "safe", "comment": "cat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZIL-4104"}
{"title_page": "Stephen Collins", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor and writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Stephen Collins\n| image              = File:Stephen Collins 2014.jpg\n| caption            = Collins in 2014\n| birth_name         = Stephen Weaver Collins\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1947|10|1}}\n| birth_place        = [[Des Moines, Iowa]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actor, writer\n| years_active       = 1974\u20132014\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Marjorie Weinman|1970|1978|end=div.}}<br />{{marriage|[[Faye Grant]]|1985 |2015|end=div.}}\n| children           = 1\n| alma_mater         = [[Amherst College]]\n}}\n'''Stephen Weaver Collins''' (born October 1, 1947) is an American actor and writer. He is known for playing [[List of 7th Heaven characters#Eric Camden|Eric Camden]] on the long-running television series ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]'' from 1996 to 2007. Since then, Collins has played the roles of Dayton King on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] TV series ''[[No Ordinary Family]]'' and Gene Porter in the television series ''[[Revolution (TV series)|Revolution]]'', father of [[Elizabeth Mitchell]]'s character, Rachel Matheson. Before ''7th Heaven'', Collins was known for his role as Commander [[List of Star Trek characters (A\u2013F)#D|Willard Decker]] in the 1979 film ''[[Star Trek: The Motion Picture]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nStephen Collins was born on October 1, 1947, in [[Des Moines, Iowa]], to mother Madeleine ([[Given name|n\u00e9e]] Robertson) and father Cyrus Stickney Collins, an airline executive.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/50/Stephen-Collins.html| title=Stephen Collins Biography (1947\u2013)| publisher=filmreference.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.amherst.edu/aboutamherst/magazine/in_memory/1939/cyruscollins| title=Cyrus S. Collins '39 \u2013 Amherst College| publisher=amherst.edu}}</ref> Collins was raised with his two older brothers in [[Hastings-on-Hudson]], New York, and attended [[Amherst College]] in Massachusetts, graduating ''[[cum laude]].''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amherst.edu/users/C/swcollins69 |title=C {{!}} Collins, Stephen W. {{!}} Amherst College |website=www.amherst.edu |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> While at Amherst, he played bass guitar in a number of bands.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvparty.com/scollins.html |title=An Interview with Stephen Collins |website=TV Party! |first=Paul M. |last=Riordan |year=1999| access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCollins is known for his role as [[List of 7th Heaven characters|Eric Camden]] in the television drama series ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]'' during the series' run from 1996 to 2007<ref>{{cite news |url=http://people.com/celebrity/the-stephen-collins-scandal-how-a-hollywood-marriage-became-a-nightmare/ |title=The Stephen Collins Scandal: How a Hollywood Marriage Became a Nightmare |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |access-date=June 26, 2018 |date=October 9, 2014 }}</ref> and for his role as Captain [[Willard Decker]] in ''[[Star Trek: The Motion Picture]].''<ref name=\"wapo2014\" /> His other notable television credits include Jake Cutter in the cult series ''[[Tales of the Gold Monkey]]'' and his role in ''[[Tattingers]]'', as well as guest appearances in ''[[The Waltons]]'', ''[[Barnaby Jones]]'', ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'', and numerous [[miniseries]] and [[made-for-television]] movies. He was nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] for his work opposite [[Ann-Margret]] in the miniseries ''[[The Two Mrs. Grenvilles]]'' and he played [[John F. Kennedy]] in the miniseries ''[[A Woman Named Jackie]]'', which won the Emmy for Best Miniseries. He also played the lead role opposite [[Lauren Hutton]] in the made-for-TV movie ''The Rhinemann Exchange'', based on [[The Rhinemann Exchange|Robert Ludlum's bestselling novel]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/10/08/showbiz/tv/who-is-stephen-collins/index.html |title=Who is Stephen Collins? |last=Leopold |first=Todd |work=CNN |access-date=March 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCollins has co-starred with [[Diane Keaton]] in both ''[[The First Wives Club]]'' (1996) and ''[[Because I Said So (film)|Because I Said So]]'' (2007). He has co-starred with [[Meredith Baxter]] in three films, ''[[All the President's Men (film)|All the President's Men]],'' ''A Woman Scorned: The [[Betty Broderick]] Story,'' and ''Her Final Fury: Betty Broderick, the Last Chapter'', both of which were made-for-television movies broadcast on [[CBS]] in 1992.\n\nIn the 2010\u201311 television season, Collins starred in the short-lived [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] series ''[[No Ordinary Family]]''.<ref>{{cite news |date=June 11, 2010 |url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Stephen-Collins-Family-1019538.aspx |title=Stephen Collins Bumped to Series Regular on ''No Ordinary Family'' |last=Stanhope |first=Kate| work=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref> On ABC's ''[[Brothers & Sisters (2006 TV series)|Brothers & Sisters]]'', he played a potential love interest for [[Ron Rifkin]]'s character [[Saul Holden]]. Collins appeared in season eight of ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'' playing [[Andy Bernard]]'s father in the episode, \"[[Garden Party (The Office)|Garden Party]]\".<ref>{{cite journal| url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/08/the-office-scoop-stephen-collins/ |title=Office Scoop: Stephen Collins Is Andy's Dad!| journal=[[TV Line]]| first= Michael| last=Ausiello| date=August 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/office-no-ordinary-familys-stephen-223805 |title='The Office': 'No Ordinary Family's' Stephen Collins to Guest Star |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 16, 2011 |access-date=June 26, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Collins began appearing in the [[NBC]] series ''[[Revolution (TV series)|Revolution]]'' as Dr. Gene Porter, the leader of the town of Willoughby and father of Rachel Matheson (played by [[Elizabeth Mitchell]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/crime/la-me-stephen-collins-20141218-story.html |title=Actor Stephen Collins admits sexual misconduct with three girls |last2=Westfall |first2=Julie |last1=Mather |first1=Kate |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=December 17, 2014 |access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> and in two episodes of ''[[Falling Skies]]'' in season three. Collins' recent guest spots include ''[[The Fosters (season 5)|The Fosters]]'', ''[[Penance (TV series)|Penance]]'', and ''[[Devious Maids]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nola.com/tv/index.ssf/2014/10/stephen_collins_former_7th_hea.html |title=Stephen Collins, former '7th Heaven' actor, under new investigation |newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]] |date=October 15, 2014 |location=New Orleans |access-date=March 27, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCollins was married to Marjorie Weinman from 1970 to 1978.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen Collins: Biography |work=[[TV Guide]] |url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/stephen-collins/bio/175302 |accessdate=May 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Collins, Stephen, 1947\u2013 |publisher=Encyclopedia.com |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-2897700030.html |accessdate=May 15, 2013}}</ref> In 1985, he married actress [[Faye Grant]], whom he had met on the set of ''[[Tales of the Gold Monkey]]'' in 1982.<ref name=\"ABC\"/>  Together they have a daughter, Kate, who was born in 1989. They separated in 2012, and, after 30 years of marriage, a final divorce decree was issued in January 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.people.com/article/stephen-collins-faye-grant-divorce-settlement |title=Stephen Collins and Faye Grant Settle Divorce |work=People |date=January 23, 2015 |accessdate=January 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/stephen-collins-and-faye-grant-split-after-27-years/ |title=Stephen Collins and Faye Grant split after 27 years |work=[[CBS News]]| last=Moraski |first=Lauren |date=May 8, 2012 |accessdate=June 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCollins is an [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]]<ref name=\"sct\">{{cite news |url=http://www.southcoasttoday.com/daily/01-01/01-25-01/c14ho157.htm |title=Stephen Collins content to be in '7th Heaven' |work=[[The Standard-Times (New Bedford)|The Standard-Times]] |location=[[New Bedford, Massachusetts]] |accessdate=January 25, 2001 |url-status=dead |agency=[[Associated Press]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040724123523/http://www.southcoasttoday.com/daily/01-01/01-25-01/c14ho157.htm |archivedate=July 24, 2004 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and a practitioner of [[Transcendental Meditation technique|Transcendental Meditation]] (TM) and has taken part in the advanced TM Yogic Flying technique since 1980.<ref>{{cite news |title=Seeking Site for a 'Peace Palace' |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/jun/14/local/me-religpalace14 |first=Bob |last=Pool |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=June 14, 2003 |page=B24}}</ref> Until October 2014, he was a national co-director of the Committee for Stress-Free Schools, which advocates practicing TM in schools and funds TM research.<ref>{{cite web |title=Committee for Stress-Free Schools: About Us |url=http://www.tmeducation.org/about-us |accessdate=August 4, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rk0JQoUi?url=http://www.tmeducation.org/about-us |archivedate=August 4, 2010 |publisher=tmeducation.org |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n==Sexual abuse allegations==\nIn October 2014, the [[New York City Police Department]] began investigating Collins after an audio tape leaked to the media revealed a male voice&mdash;purported to be that of Collins&mdash;admitting to past sexual abuse of a minor.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news |first=Lauren |last=Effron |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/stephen-collins-denies-pedophile-confessing-sexual-misconduct-girls/story?id=27728607 |title=Stephen Collins Denies He's a Pedophile |work=[[ABC News]] |date=December 20, 2014 |accessdate=March 18, 2018}}</ref> A [[Los Angeles Police Department]] spokesperson stated that Collins had been investigated by the department in 2012 after receiving a claim from 40 years earlier regarding sexual abuse. The LAPD further stated that its investigation did not allow it to \"substantiate the allegation\" against Collins.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Shimon |last1=Prokupecz |first2=Steve |last2=Almas |title=Source: '7th Heaven' actor subject of molestation allegations |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/10/07/showbiz/stephen-collins-molestation-probe/ |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=October 7, 2014 |accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-stephen-collins-7th-heaven-up-tv-20141007-story.html |title='7th Heaven' pulled after Stephen Collins molestation allegations |work=Los Angeles Times |date=October 7, 2014 |accessdate=October 7, 2014 |first=Yvonne |last=Villareal}}</ref>\n\nIn a December 2014 interview with ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine, Collins admitted he committed \"inappropriate sexual conduct with three female minors\" in 1973, 1982, and 1994.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ann |last=Oldenburg |title=Stephen Collins: 'I did something terribly wrong' |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2014/12/17/stephen-collins-admits-sexual-abuse-terribly-wrong-katie-couric/20524835/ |work=[[USA Today]] |date=December 17, 2014 |accessdate=December 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/nyc-crime/7th-heaven-dad-stephen-collins-admits-sexually-abusing-girl-article-1.1965747 |first=Meg| last=Wagner| first2=Thomas| last2=Tracy| first3=Nancy| last3=Dillon| title=Stephen Collins, pastor-dad in \u20187th Heaven,\u2019 admits to sexually abusing underage girl, exposing himself to 2 others (audio) |work=[[New York Daily News]] |date=October 7, 2014 |accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref> A profile by ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that he apologized directly to one of the girls.<ref name=\"wapo2014\">{{cite news |first=Abby |last=Phillip |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2014/12/17/7th-heaven-dad-stephen-collins-admits-to-sexually-abusing-three-girls/ |title=\u20187th Heaven\u2019 dad Stephen Collins admits to sexually abusing three girls |work=The Washington Post |date=December 17, 2014 |access-date=March 22, 2018 |language=en-US |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> He has stated that his inappropriate conduct was motivated by arrogance and youth, not [[pedophilia]]. To explain his motivation, he spoke about an older woman who repeatedly exposed herself to him when he was between the ages of 10 and 15.<ref name=\"ABC\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!class=\"unsortable|Notes\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[The Waltons]]''\n|Todd Clarke\n|Episode: \"The Abdication\"\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Brink's: The Great Robbery]]''\n|Agent Donald Nash\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[The Rhinemann Exchange]]''\n|David Spaulding\n|Miniseries<br>3 episodes\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Charlie's Angels]]''\n|Steve Carmody \n|Episode: \"Angel Come Home\"\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[The Henderson Monster]]''\n|Pete Casimir\n|TV movie\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1981\n|''[[Great Performances]]''\n|Morton Fullerton\n|Episode: \"Edith Wharton: Looking Back\"\n|-\n|''[[Summer Solstice (1981 film)|Summer Solstice]]''\n|Young Joshua Turner\n|rowspan=2|TV movie\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1982\n|''[[Inside the Third Reich (film)|Inside the Third Reich]]''\n|[[Karl Hanke]]\n|-\n|''[[Tales of the Gold Monkey]]''\n|Jake Cutter\n|Main role (21 episodes)\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Chiefs (miniseries)|Chiefs]]''\n|Billy Lee\n|Miniseries<br>3 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1984\n|''[[Threesome]]''\n|Peter Hatten\n|rowspan=2|TV movie\n|-\n|''[[Dark Mirror (1984 film)|Dark Mirror]]''\n|Jim Eiseley\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[The Hitchhiker (TV series)|The Hitchhiker]]''\n|Todd Fields\n|Episode: \"And If We Dream\"\n|-\n|1986\